To show that (A △ B) △ C ≠ A △ (B △ C) with respect to the Cartesian product, we will first find the symmetric difference (△) of A and B, and then of B and C. After that, we will find the symmetric difference of the results and compare them.

Recall that the symmetric difference of two sets A and B is given by (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B).

1. Find A △ B:
A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}
A ∩ B = {2, 3}
A △ B = {1, 4}

2. Find B △ C:
B ∪ C = {1, 2, 3, 4}
B ∩ C = {2, 4}
B △ C = {1, 3}

Now we will find the symmetric difference of the results:

3. Find (A △ B) △ C:
(A △ B) ∪ C = {1, 4} ∪ {1, 2, 4} = {1, 2, 4}
(A △ B) ∩ C = {1, 4} ∩ {1, 2, 4} = {1, 4}
(A △ B) △ C = {2}

4. Find A △ (B △ C):
A ∪ (B △ C) = {1, 2, 3} ∪ {1, 3} = {1, 2, 3}
A ∩ (B △ C) = {1, 2, 3} ∩ {1, 3} = {1, 3}
A △ (B △ C) = {2}

Since both (A △ B) △ C and A △ (B △ C) result in the same set {2}, the statement (A △ B) △ C ≠ A △ (B △ C) is false with respect to the Cartesian product.
